# 1\. Introduction

In this programming assignment, you will be building off your previous implementation in project 0\. You must implement various additional kernel syscalls and cpu interrupts. By the end of the project, you will implement a few more CPU scheduling algorithms and multithreading/multiprocessing primitives.

**Programming language**: The assignment will be implemented in Python. 

**Cooperation and third party code**: This is a **group** programming assignment, and your group should implement the code on your own. Your group may not share final solutions with anyone outside of your group, and your group must write up your own work, expressing it in your own words/notation. Third party code including libraries are not allowed (built in python libraries are fine).

# 2\. Environment setup

The simulator runs using standard Python without any installed libraries. Feel free to use any modern Python version [(which you can find here)](https://www.python.org/), however your code will be tested using Python 3.10.12. You should avoid writing any code that is OS dependent as no test will require this and it could cause problems for grading.

**new**:

Process type is added as an argument to new\_process\_arrived. This will be used when implementing the multilevel scheduler. Process\_type can be either “Foreground” or “Background” depending on the type of the new process. This value can be ignored for FCFS, Priority and RR schedulers.

**Entirely new methods (copy paste them at the bottom of your kernel.py class)**:  
	\# This method is triggered when the currently running process requests to initialize a new semaphore.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def syscall\_init\_semaphore(self, semaphore\_id: int, initial\_value: int):  
    		return  
      
	\# This method is triggered when the currently running process calls p() on an existing semaphore.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def syscall\_semaphore\_p(self, semaphore\_id: int) \-\> PID:  
    		return self.running.pid

	\# This method is triggered when the currently running process calls v() on an existing semaphore.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def syscall\_semaphore\_v(self, semaphore\_id: int) \-\> PID:  
    		return self.running.pid

	\# This method is triggered when the currently running process requests to initialize a new mutex.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def syscall\_init\_mutex(self, mutex\_id: int):  
    		return

	\# This method is triggered when the currently running process calls lock() on an existing mutex.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def syscall\_mutex\_lock(self, mutex\_id: int) \-\> PID:  
    		return self.running.pid

	\# This method is triggered when the currently running process calls unlock() on an existing mutex.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def syscall\_mutex\_unlock(self, mutex\_id: int) \-\> PID:  
    		return self.running.pid

	\# This function represents the hardware timer interrupt.  
	\# It is triggered every 10 microseconds and is the only way a kernel can track passing time.  
	\# Do not use real time to track how much time has passed as time is simulated.  
	\# DO NOT rename or delete this method. DO NOT change its arguments.  
	def timer\_interrupt(self) \-\> PID:  
    		return self.running.pid

These are new methods that the simulator will call for the new simulations. You will notice that some of them **do not** return a PID and thus can not cause a context switch.

3.3 Tracking Time  
The only way for a kernel to track short periods of time is by counting clock cycles, external timers, or internal registers managed by the CPU. For this simulator, we will keep track of time using the timer\_interrupt. This interrupt handler is called every 10 microseconds  (0.010ms). As previously mentioned, the built in python time APIs will not be helpful in this simulator as **time is simulated and is not real time**. For this reason, the timer interrupt is the only way for your kernel to keep track of time. Tracking time will be necessary for your implementation of the Multilevel and Round Robin schedulers. However, since the kernel can only keep track of time in 10 microsecond increments, this has some interesting consequences when implementing these algorithms which will be discussed in their implementation sections.

# 4\. What to implement

4.1 Round Robin scheduler (RR)  
You must implement a Round Robin scheduling algorithm. This scheduler will give each process a time quantum of 40 microseconds (0.040ms). However, due to the difficulties of tracking time in a kernel, we have to make estimations. For this RR scheduler, every time there is a timer interrupt, **assume that the running process has been running since the previous timer interrupt.** To understand what this means, consider the following scenario in RR1.  
![][image3]  
	Here the correct output may look a little strange. After process 1 finishes execution, it switches to process 3\. However, Process 3 does not run for the full 40 microseconds. It only runs for 35 microseconds. This becomes a little more clear if we add the timer interrupts to the logs.  
![][image4]  
	As you can see, Process 1 finishes in between two timer interrupts. Since they are our only way of keeping track of time, there is no way for the kernel to know if process 3 has been running for 10ms, 5ms, 1ms, etc when the next timer interrupt happens at 0.900ms. For our implementation, you should always assume the process has been running for the full 10 microseconds. This is why process 3 gets context switched early by 5 microseconds.

	An even more extreme example can be seen in RR2 where an interrupt happens **right after** a context switch.  
![][image5]  
![][image6]  
	In this example, even though process 5 has barely executed at all by the time the timer interrupt occurs, the RR scheduler will assume that it has been running for 10 microseconds. This results in it only running for 30 microseconds.

For a visual explanation see the discussion video [here](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1lXRhpGCRokoHzQjWbOrTaW8DvObkTofJ/view?usp=sharing).

4.2 Multilevel Scheduler  
You must implement a Multilevel scheduling algorithm with 2 levels. The first level is Foreground and the second is Background. Each level operates independently of the other and with different scheduling algorithms.  
Foreground Level: This level will use the RR scheduling algorithm. Processes with process\_type \== Foreground should be placed in this level and scheduled via the RR scheduling algorithm as described above.  
Background Level: This level will use the FCFS scheduling algorithm implemented in project 0\. Processes with process\_type \== Background should be placed in this level and scheduled via the FCFS scheduling algorithm.  
Switching Levels: Your scheduler will switch between running processes in the Foreground level and processes in the Background Level. 50% of the time it will run processes in the Foreground and 50% of the time it will run processes in the Background. It should switch between levels every 200 microseconds. If there are no processes in the other level, it should not switch. When the scheduling algorithm switches to another level, it should stay committed to that level until there are no more processes to run in that level, or 190-200 microseconds have passed (the range is due to the exact same reasons as the range of 30-40 microseconds in RR scheduling). If you try to switch to another level and there are no processes to run in that level, you should continue running your current level and begin another 190-200 microsecond commitment.

For a visual explanation see the discussion video [here](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1lXRhpGCRokoHzQjWbOrTaW8DvObkTofJ/view?usp=sharing).

4.3 Semaphore / Mutex  
You must implement semaphores and mutexes for FCFS, Priority, and RR scheduling. (**Note**: This does not include the Multilevel scheduling algorithm. You will not need to implement Semaphores or Mutexes for this algorithm) Before a semaphore or mutex are used, some process will call syscall\_init\_semaphore with the id of the new semaphore and its initial value. The same is true for mutexes, but they do not have an initial value.  
After being initialized, processes will call p and v for semaphores or lock and unlock for mutexes. According to the rules of semaphores and mutexes, processes should be prevented from executing appropriately.  
When it comes time to continue the execution of a process according to the rules of semaphores and mutexes, the different scheduling algorithms will have different rules. For FCFS and RR, release the process with the lowest PID that is blocked by this semaphore/mutex. For Priority, release the process that has the highest priority according to Priority scheduling.  
When implementing Semaphores for FCFS, it should be non-preemptive. Meaning, if a process that arrived before the currently running process is released, there should not be an immediate context switch to it (**note**: Mutexes will not be tested with FCFS as it does not really make sense. I will leave you to consider why that is true).  
You can assume that no process will call lock on a mutex twice before calling unlock and you can assume that unlock will only be called by a process that has previously locked the mutex.
